node.text:
A trip to Udupi would have been incomplete, had I not paid a visit to its famous Shree Krishna Temple. On a recent trip organised by the Ministry of Tourism, India, I toured this ancient temple that has a fantastic history. In the early 13th-century, sage Madhvacharya established the base of the Maadhva faction of Hinduism in Udupi. He set forth dualism, challenging the traditional Advaita philosophy. To do so, Madhvacharya began to worship lord Krishna at this site. Krishna, one of the many incarnations of Lord Vishnu was pleased by Madhvacharya’s devotion and turned to his praying. Thereon this temple turned into a major pilgrimage destination. I love the humble architecture of this temple, resembling an Aashram with its eight Matha(s) namely Admaru, Kaniyoor, Krishnapura, Palimaru, Pejavara, Puttige, Sodhe and Shirur Matha. Collectively these are known as the Ashta Mathagalu. Daily worship is offered at these holy Matha(s), and each has its very-own deity, the Pattada Devaru. Krishna Matha, in particular, is renowned worldwide for its sacred rituals of Dvaita philosophy. All Matha expenses are borne by deliberate contributions of the devotees! Since Madhvacharya was also the founder of the Dwaita school of Vedanta, mass feeding of school students is facilitated at the temple every day. This service is called the giving of 'Anna Prasada.' Shri Krishna Temple is enclosed by many thousand-year-old temples and is a wonderful site to visit in Udupi. Been here? Tell me about your experience.

After visiting the Udupi Shree Krishna Temple, we drove to Hasta Shilpa Heritage Village Museum in Manipal. Nestled amidst wild jackfruit trees, this living museum is a gathering of traditional houses that have been well-preserved for generations. Vijayanath Shenoy, the first owner of this home, had dreamt about building a one-of-its-kind ethnographic museum, and so he decided to bring his own traditional home into play. This home was 'originally' built in the 1980s as a courtyard house. Be it cooking utensils or gleaned material from forsaken structures, Hasta Shilpa; still retains every uncia of its eclectic collection of artefacts and furnishings from different eras. In a way that causes surprise, Vijayanath Shenoy left this house as the advertising surrounding the home eventually led to a loss of privacy. Consequently, the house outlasted for more than 15 years. Until Hasta Shilpa Trust restored it with the financial assistance of TATA. This residential museum was inaugurated on 14th November 2017 and is open from November through February.

Together with OPPO Reno 5 Pro, I am embarking on a journey to explore four offbeat landmarks of Indore, a 16th-century city with a hidden legacy lurking behind its new-age streets. Each of these unique landmarks illustrates, the best of Holkar dynasty and following eras, and I hope you enjoy this tour just as much as I did.
___________________________
Kanch Mandir: Constructed in 1903 by Hukumchand Seth, this Jain temple boasts walls and ceilings ornamented with thousands of tiny multi-coloured mirrors. The temple also houses multiple Palki's made of gold and silver. 
___________________________
Lal Bagh Palace: Back in the 19th-century, this royal residence served as the official residence of the Holkar Maharajah. It is designed in neoclassical and baroque architectural styles and is now an ASI protected monument.
___________________________
Annapurna Temple: One of the oldest temples of Indore, that resembles the famous Meenakshi Temple of Madurai. Built-in 9th-century, this temple is devoted to Annapurna, the goddess of food, and boasts revered shrines, intricate carvings and four stunning life-size elephant statues. 
___________________________
Footi Kothi: Some call it a haunted manor, some use it to reinvigorate their creative juices, either way, these ancient ruins have some of the best red stone architecture and columns that you will see in Indore
___________________________
No gimbals, or handheld devices, were employed, to film this video! I only used OPPO Reno 5 Pro's in-built features such as AI, ultra HD, ultra-Steady mode etc. Reno 5 Pro is an excellent phone for travellers who like to travel light and would love to own a light-weighted phone that pretty much replaces the need for a regular DSLR.

While we all wished for 2021 to be the year of difference; OPPO well-timed the launch of its all-new Reno 5 Pro on January 18th to turn our wishes into a reality! Get this phone, if you want your lightweight phone to function just as fine as, a DSLR. With this unboxing, I am unveiling the technical features of the Reno 5 Pro while, in my upcoming videos, I will reveal how to put it to application. Feel free to drop in any questions that you may have! (If you ask me, I am loving using this phone and I am sure you will too) 
___________________________
WHAT'S NEW?
Reno 5 Pro comes with 5G connectivity to ensure speed never fails you. With 5G you can expect fast downloads, fast processing and far better happiness quotient. With MediaTek's 7nm-class Dimensity 1000+ the 5G chip delivers 'stronger' connection stability, top-notch graphics, superior performance and faster speeds. This feature is well-paired with 65W Super VOOC 2.0 charger that gets you 100% charge in 30-minutes and a super power-saving mode. Two words: Incredible and Reliable!
___________________________
PHOTOGRAPHY AND VIDEOGRAPHY:
With OPPO Reno 5 Pro - all my photos and videos come out great, irrespective of the time I take them! Big thanks to new "AI Highlight, Ultra Night and Live HDR Modes," each picture turns out to be vibrant and clear, whether its early morning or late night. The consistency of the lighting is just outstanding! They even have a dual-video mode where you can record two backdrops at the same time. In Slow-motion mode - you can film from 120 frames per second to 960 frames per second.
___________________________
FEATURES:
Android v11 8 GB RAM 128 GB, Non-Expandable
Octa-core (2.6 GHz Quad Core + 2 GHz Quad core) MediaTek Dimensity 1000+ 
Display: 6.55 inches 402 PPI, Super AMOLED90 Hz refresh rate
Camera: 64 + 8 + 2 + 2 MP Quad Primary Cameras, 32 MP Front Camera and LED Flash
Battery: 4350 mAhVOOC Charging 2.0USB Type-C Port
Dual SIM: Nano + Nano
Supports Indian bands, VoLTE, Fingerprint sensor and USB OTG Support
STARTS 35,990 onwards

Fringed with palm, banana and other trees on either side, the Colombo Galle main road is a road to delight. I must have stuck my head out of the car window, for the most part of the journey as I couldn't stop getting enough gentle, cool, ocean breeze touching my face. What halted our drive? The Amarsena Turtle Hatchery, in the Kosgoda Sea Turtle Conservation Project, that I was visiting today to appreciate the good work being done, by the volunteers. Kosgoda is a small coastal town, famed for its sea turtle hatcheries. What's amazing about this village is that it's full of conservationists who want to protect the endangered species. In an order to do so, individual turtle conservationists run their own hatcheries. One of such hatcheries was built by Amarasena Fernando in 1966. In 2004, when Tsunami badly hit the coastal areas of Sri Lanka, this hatchery became home to many deformed and blind sea turtles. Only about 7, sea turtle varieties exist today, out of which 5, are found in Sri Lanka. These are the Green Turtle, the Hawksbill, the Loggerhead, the Olive Ridley and the Leatherback. At Amarsena Turtle Hatchery, I engaged with and had a look at, all of these five endangered species. Read on: https://www.krazybutterfly.com/amarsena-turtle-hatchery-kosgoda/

node.text: Ceylon Cinnamon, they say is the truest and the finest of its kind. During my last visit to Sri Lanka, in November, I paid a visit to a cinnamon factory in Ayagama, a village near Colombo. This video captures the entire making process of true cinnamon. First they shave the outer and the inner barks then dry it up to make cinnamon quills. Along the factory tour, I also learned about several health benefits of this exotic medicinal herb, which is one of mother nature’s greatest gift to humankind. Here’s a preview of my visit to Samarakkody Holdings @browngold_cinnamon, a brand engaged in processing True Ceylon Cinnamon from harvesting to packaging 💜 #samarakkody_holdings #cinnamonfactory #cinnamon #cinnamonmaking #travelwithkrazybutterfly

My Ahmedabad trip kicked off with an incredible Heritage Walk as we plodded across its historic lanes decked with antiquated architecture including this ancient fairy tale temple that deftly drew me into its fold. Shree Swaminarayan Mandir Kalupur is the first Temple of the Swaminarayan Sampraday in Ahmedabad that received its first shrine by the British Imperial Government however its construction was personally entrusted by Swaminarayan. Being the 1st-temple of the Swaminarayan Sampraday, this temple was built as per the scriptural norms: boasting intricate carvings in pure Burma-teak. It was an incredible experience to visit it in person and to get a chance to admire its sculptural art depicting deities, and religious icons portraying axiomatic religion and Indian culture. I’ll shortly roll out a blog on this cultural heritage: until then, take a look at its Magnificent built and its wooden carvings, some of which even depict the 1857 uprising, India's first war of Independence. Each one of its coloured arch and palatial carvings is a bright shade, a pattern that stands out in most Swaminarayan temples.

While gallivanting around Galle Lighthouse, you will notice an unusual whitewashed building with a dash of Islamic detailing. This all-embracing architectural surprise is none other than the century-old Meeran Mosque. Even though I didn't get a chance, to explore the Mosque from within, I was told, its facade bears the same design as that of a Portuguese/Dutch cathedral. With Galle Fort in the foreground, and a stunning landscape stretching in the backdrop, this elevated 19th-century Mosque stands out like a beacon facing Mecca. Built by Ahamed Haji Ismail, a devoted wealthy Muslim, Meeran Mosque does not abstain a woman's visit to a confined prayer room. At Meeran, female visitors are allowed to explore the main areas as a touring display. Their prayer area, however, is in a separate building. From within, the Mosque features a niche in the wall, an exquisitely sculpted Mihrab, decorated with domes and captivating Italian flooring. The elegantly luxurious high ceiling opens up the passageways and throws a spotlight on the chandeliers, and the embedded motifs of doors and windows. Wherein, the sculpted arch marks the direction to pray. Meeran Mosque also has a well-manicured lawn for the worshippers to relax and converse. Just make sure to wear appropriate clothing while visiting this beautiful Mosque. Read on: https://www.krazybutterfly.com/best-things-to-do-in-galle-sri-lanka/

When I went photo raiding the Galle Fort! This interesting UNESCO World Heritage site was built by the Portuguese in the late 15th-century and strengthened by the Dutch in the mid-16th century. Despite the crumbling compositions of the middle ages, Galle Fort still retains its archaeological lustre. This heritage monument is also known as the Dutch Fort, as many Nederlanders still own properties inside it. Together with the Sri Lankan government, the Dutch plan on converting the Galle Fort into one of the present-day wonders of the world. To explore this Fort of pristine beauty, overpass the trail of life-size statues of uniformed soldiers and follow the ramparts to learn about many untold stories about the Fort's survival history. node.text:
When travelling through Galle Fort neighbourhood, make sure to stop by Groote Kerk, the 17th-century Dutch Reformed Church near the Fort entrance. This one right here, is the oldest protestant church in Sri Lanka. But that’s just one reason to want to visit it. Another reason is its captivating Doric style architecture, built 39ft above sea level - that being the highest point of the Galle Fort. Originally, this site was a Portuguese Capuchin Convent and then later in 1755, Lord of Spanbroek donated money to build a church here to get his daughter baptised on August 24th of 1755. Later on, Brits made a few changes to the church, like installing a stained glass window and adding a communion rail. Although what makes this church truly awesome to gaze at, is its unique double scroll moulding. The central part of the church is separated, by two arches, and the interiors stand out with its hexagonal podium and a star-studded ceiling. The triangular upper part of the wall at the end of the ridged roofs is finished off with three finials. Haven’t been here yet? Well then now is the time 😊 Read on: https://www.krazybutterfly.com/best-things-to-do-in-galle-sri-lanka/

To walk into an estate, that brings ancient architecture alive in the blink of an eye, is like walking into a wakeful dream. One such dream was conceived through and through by Vijayanath Shenoy in 1984. He founded Hasta Shilpa Heritage Village for the love of preserving ancient art, and no we are not talking ordinary art! We are talking architectural masterpieces and relics of demolished old houses put together like an anthologised literature. Hasta Shilpa Heritage Village unfolds the history of Heritage, house after house, making you wend your way into what I’d call dreaming, just differently! In this frame, I’m expressing admiration for Peshwa Wada, an elegant house that once belonged to the Peshwa family of the North-Western Karnataka.
